R Markdown Demonstration using Breast Imaging Data

Data Citation: This breast cancer database was obtained from the University of Wisconsin Hospitals, Madison from Dr. William H. Wolberg. See Machine learning techniques to diagnose breast cancer from image-processed nuclear features of fine needle aspirates. Cancer Letters 1994; 77:163-171.

Step 1: Load Packages

We will be using two packages in addition to base R. Amelia is for missing data and will provide us with a plot of missingness. Caret is primarly from classification and regression trees, but has many features that are useful for data preprocessing. We will be using a function to partition data into training and testing.

Step 3: Partition data into training and testing sets

Many ways to do this. Using CreateDataPartition in caret package. Allows you to specify factor outcome so proportion with outcome is similar in training and testing dataset. We are specifying a 70/30 split training/testing. Remember to set seed so that the results are reproducible.

set.seed(100)
train.indices<-createDataPartition(y=bc.data$outcome,p=0.7,list=FALSE)

training<-bc.data[train.indices,]
testing<-bc.data[-train.indices,]

Step 4: Construct logistic regression models to predict Malignancy

  • Model 1: Include all features
  • Model 2: Include only clump thickness

Step 5: Compare accuracy of two different models in test set

This is a simple evaluation . We are obtaining predicted probabilities for test set using the model built on the training set and rounding to 0/1 for classification to benign (0) or malignant (1). We are testing both of our models in the test set. Typically, these types of comparisons are done using cross-validation within the training set. That will be covered in Module 2. There is also code for generating calibration curves, which will be discussed in more detail in Module 2.

fitted.results <- predict(model.1,testing,type='response')
fitted.results.p <- ifelse(fitted.results > 0.5,1,0)

testing.outcome<-(as.numeric(testing$outcome)-1)

misClasificError <- mean(fitted.results.p != testing.outcome, na.rm=T)
print(paste('Accuracy Model 1',1-misClasificError))
## [1] "Accuracy Model 1 0.965853658536585"
testProbs <- data.frame(obs = testing$outcome,
                        pred.logit=fitted.results)

calPlotData<-calibration(obs ~ pred.logit, data = testProbs, class="Malignant", cuts=5)

xyplot(calPlotData, auto.key = list(columns = 2))

fitted.results.rmodel <- predict(model.2,testing,type='response')
fitted.results.rmodel.p <- ifelse(fitted.results.rmodel > 0.5,1,0)

misClasificError <- mean(fitted.results.rmodel.p != testing.outcome, na.rm=T)
print(paste('Accuracy Model 2',1-misClasificError))
## [1] "Accuracy Model 2 0.842105263157895"
testProbs.rmodel <- data.frame(obs = testing$outcome,
                        pred.logit.rmodel=fitted.results.rmodel)

calPlotData.rmodel<-calibration(obs ~ pred.logit.rmodel, data = testProbs.rmodel, class="Malignant", cuts=5)

xyplot(calPlotData.rmodel, auto.key = list(columns = 2))
